		<td><b>Re: Was ARM originally cheaper than 68000?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In 1986 the x86 first-mover advantage wasn't insurmountably huge yet. But the 68k's might have been.<br /><br />Performance-for-cost-wise, the Acorn Archimedes was neither drastically better (similar MIPS/MHz and MHz) nor cheaper than 68k or x86-based machines (Fair comparison: Amiga 1000 (1985; 256k RAM) for $1300, Amiga 2000 (1987; 512k RAM) for $1500 vs Archimedes 305 (1987; 512k RAM) for £800≈$1300)<br /><br />Whenever I've sat down and actually run the numbers on real-world performance ... RISC architectures have always been a good deal more marketing woo then actually drastically better. Even the much-vaunted DEC Alpha seems to have really only been impressive because it was easier to make their design run at higher total power dissipation than other architectures.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


