	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Was ARM originally cheaper than 68000?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />When the RISC ideas were first floated, they were really good ones. CPUs were blowing a huge portion of their die space on underused instructions, decoding logic, and microcode, and there weren't just weren't enough transistors left for pipelining. Plus memory access speeds were roughly on par with CPU speed, so memory bandwidth wasn't such a massive bottleneck. There was a reason that everyone except for Intel abandoned CISC architectures in the early 90s: PowerPC and MIPS chips were crushing everyone else on speed and efficiency.<br /><br />Modern manufacturing processes mean that there's now way more transistors available to CPU designers, and now the heavier decoding costs for CISC are negligible. Combine that with Intel's heroic best-in-the-business efforts to pipeline, reorder, and branch predict the hell out of the execution stream and more compact code representation that make better use of memory bandwidth and suddenly RISC turned out to be a bit of a dead end.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


